2010-11-21 Marcello Sega <sega@icp.uni-stuttgart.de>

 * adresso.c, adresso.h, angle.h, angledist.h, bin.c, bin.h, binary_file.c,
 binary_file.h, blockfile_tcl.c, blockfile_tcl.h, bmhtf-nacl.h, buckingham.h,
 cells.c, cells.h, comfixed.h, comforce.h, communication.c, communication.h,
 config.c, config.h, constraint.c, debug.c, debug.h, debye_hueckel.h,
 dihedral.h, domain_decomposition.c, domain_decomposition.h, dpd.c, dpd.h,
 elc.c, elc.h, endangledist.h, energy.c, energy.h, ewald.c, ewald.h, fene.h,
 forces.h, gb.h, ghosts.h, global.c, global.h, grid.c, grid.h, harmonic.h,
 hertzian.h, iccp3m.c, iccp3m.h, imd.c, imd.h, initialize.c, integrate.c,
 integrate.h, interaction_data.c, interaction_data.h, lb.c, lb.h, lj.h,
 ljangle.h, ljcos.h, ljcos2.h, ljgen.c, ljgen.h, maggs.c, maggs.h,
 magnetic_non_p3m__methods.c, magnetic_non_p3m__methods.h, mdlc_correction.c,
 mdlc_correction.h, metadynamics.c, metadynamics.h, mmm1d.c, mmm1d.h, mmm2d.c,
 mmm2d.h, modes.c, mol_cut.h, morse.h, myconfig-sample.h, nemd.c, nemd.h,
 overlap.h, p3m-charges.c, p3m-charges.h, p3m-dipoles.c, p3m-dipoles.h, p3m.c,
 p3m.h, particle_data.c, particle_data.h, polymer.c, polymer.h, pressure.c,
 pressure.h, random.c, random.h, rattle.h, reaction_field.h, soft_sphere.h,
 statistics.c, statistics.h, statistics_chain.c, statistics_chain.h,
 statistics_cluster.c, statistics_cluster.h, statistics_fluid.c,
 statistics_fluid.h, statistics_molecule.c, steppot.h, subt_lj.h, tab.h,
 thermostat.c, thermostat.h, topology.c, topology.h, tunable_slip.h, tuning.c,
 tuning.h, utils.c, utils.h, uwerr.c, uwerr.h, verlet.c, verlet.h,
 virtual_sites.c, virtual_sites.h: This is a small guide to the new naming
 convention in ESPResSo.  Tcl commands parsing functions in ESPResSo were
 somehow heterogeneous both in logical structure and in naming convention: I
 tried to make some order as explained below. Summarizing, now every function
 involving the Tcl interpreter(*) has one of the following forms 
 tclcommand_SOMETHING tclcallback_SOMETHING tclprint_SOMETHING  Please notice
 that this is still a test version: the naming convention can still (will) be
 changed, and not every combination of #defines in myconfig.h has been tried,
 so some problems might still pop out. Feel free to contact me
 (sega@icp.uni-stuttgart.de) (a) about problematic as well as successful
 merges -good news are always welcome- with your actual branch (b) if some
 code got broken (c) to suggest improvements, or changes in the naming scheme.
  (*) besides very few exceptions like: functions commented out, not used
 anywhere in the code, or marked as experimental (hence, which are supposed
 anyway to be cleaned/checked),  the mpi_gather_runtime_errors(),
 on_program_start() appinit(), parse_*_list(), and init_tcl() functions. Some
 UWerr functions using the interpreter were also not changed, because new tcl
 commands are created within the module, and need probably a different
 treatment.  The details of the naming convention follows. 
 ********************************************************************* TCL
 COMMANDS AND RELATED
 ********************************************************************* All C
 functions associated to an ESPResSo tcl command have now the form 
 tclcommand_COMMAND()  where COMMAND corresponds without any exception to the
 name of the corresponding tcl command.  This should make rather easy to spot
 them in the code.  For example,  grep "tclcommand_part\>" *.[ch]  searches
 for the references to the "part" command. 
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------  When
 the first argument of a command needs to be parsed, as in the case of 'inter
 coulomb', the name of the parsing function is always 
 tclcommand_COMMAND_parse_SUBCOMMAND()  again, with strict correspondence to
 the tcl interface (this was not always the case before).  Suppose you want to
 search for all possible ways of calling the 'inter' command, then just  grep
 "tclcommand_inter_parse_[a-z]\+" *.[ch] 
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------  The
 functions parsing one level deeper are called 
 tclcommand_COMMAND_SUBCOMMAND_parse_ARGUMENT()  so, for example, the function
 which parses 'inter coulomb p3m' is  tclcommand_inter_coulomb_parse_p3m() 
 After this level, the way parsing functions are organized is too
 heterogeneous to find a unifiying naming convention without rewriting code,
 hence, all subsequent options are just appended after an underscore: 
 tclcommand_COMMAND_SUBCOMMAND_parse_ARGUMENT_OPTION()  Thus, the function
 that parses 'inter coulomb p3m tune' is 
 tclcommand_inter_coulomb_parse_p3m_tune()  The strict correspondence to the
 tcl command is also lost at this level, as for example the
 tclcommand_inter_coulomb_parse_p3m_tune() function is used to parse both the
 'tune' and the 'tunev2' options. 
 ---------------------------------------------------------------------- In
 ESPResSo, some functions involving the tcl interpreter are used just to print
 out some information, and do not parse anything (the opposite often happens).
 Even though in many cases they are also performing some operation but jut
 I/O, they have been called  tclcommand_COMMAND_print_SOMETHING  like in 
 tclcommand_inter_print_all or tclcommand_inter_print_bonded  Not in all cases
 it was possible to relate SOMETHING to a tcl command option. 
 **********************************************************************
 CALLBACKS
 **********************************************************************  All
 callbacks have now either the form  tclcallback_NAME  where NAME is the tcl
 name of the variable addressed, or they point to some default read-only
 message, like  tclcallback_ro() or tclcallback_thermo_ro(). 
 **********************************************************************
 printXYZToResult() FUNCTIONS
 **********************************************************************  All
 functions printXYZToResult() have been renamed to tclprint_to_result_XYZ() 
 ********************************************************************** MISC
 **********************************************************************  In
 addition, going through the code, all functions (not just parsers) which are
 not called anywhere have been marked with a comment like  /* TODO: this
 function is not used anywhere. To be removed? */ 
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------  This
 patch includes also some minor changes to clean the code. 
 ********************************************************************** EOF

2010-11-19 Mingyang Hu <mingyang@cmu.edu>

 * constraint.c, constraint.h, doc/ug/analysis.tex, doc/ug/part.tex,
 interaction_data.h, statistics.c, statistics.h: Add penetrable option to
 constraints; Add analyze gyration_tensor command  Add option "penetrable" to
 wall, sphere, cylinder, and maze constraint, so allow particles to pass
 throught the constraint surface. Add command "analyze gyration_tensor", which
 calculate the gyration tensor of a type of particles and returns the squared
 radius of gyration, asphericity, acylindricity, relative shape anisotropy,
 eigenvalues in descending order and their corresponding eigenvectors.

2010-11-19 Olaf Lenz <olenz@icp.uni-stuttgart.de>

 * doc/logo/logo_on_transparent.png: Added logo with transparent background.

2010-11-16 Olaf Lenz <olenz@icp.uni-stuttgart.de>

 * constraint.h: Small fixes to Rudolf's commits.

2010-11-16 Rudolf Weeber <weeber@icp.uni-stuttgart.de>

 * constraint.c, constraint.h, energy.c: Correction to external magnetic filed
 energy  * Prevent segfault in 'analyze energy' when a magnetic filed
 constraint is set * Add missing sign in energy = -<dipole_moment, field> *
 Energy of dipoles interacting with field now is still considered, when no
 dipole-dipole interaction is active

